\begin_layout Title
Size-dependent clustering in phytoplankton communities in a 3D environment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Coralie Picoche, William R.
 Young, Frédéric Barraquand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Address
\noindent
\align center
Institute of Mathematics of Bordeaux, University of Bordeaux and CNRS, Talence,
 France
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Phytoplankton communities are among the most important photosynthetic groups
 on Earth, being at the bottom of the marine food chain, and responsible
 for half the global primary production 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "field_primary_1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Their contribution to ecosystem functions is only matched by their significance
 for more theoretical studies focusing on coexistence within a single trophic
 level.
 Indeed, phytoplankton communities are characterized by a surprisingly high
 biodiversity (up to hundreds of species within multiple genera and even
 classes in volumes as small as 10 mL), an observation which has led to
 the formulation of the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

paradox of the plankton
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hutchinson_paradox_1961"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This term refers to the conflict between the observed diversity maintenance
 of species competing for similar resources in a seemingly homogeneous environme
nt, and theoretical expectations of a few species outcompeting the others.
 Phytoplankton models for coexistence are now as diverse as their model
 organism 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "record_paradox_2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Proposed mechanisms to escape from competitive exclusion are based on the
 general literature on coexistence, which includes non-linear responses
 to the environment in a temporally fluctuating environment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "li_effects_2016,chesson_updates_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, in a nonspatial setting, i.e.
 keeping the premise of a homogeneous environment.
 Such assumption needs to be challenged, as we know that spatialized models
 including a heterogeneous environment and/or non-mixed populations can
 lead to highly different outcomes from their nonspatial counterparts 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "law_population_2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This is even more relevant as field observations themselves have higlighted
 phytoplankton patchiness for more than a century 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bainbridge_size_1957"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, from the macro- to the micro-scale 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "leonard_interannual_2001,doubell_high-resolution_2006,font-munoz_advection_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Phytoplankton patchiness can at least be partly explained by the hydrodynamics
 of their environment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "martin_phytoplankton_2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

: their size being mostly below the size of the smallest eddy (i.e., the Kolmogoro
v scale) in a typical environment such as the ocean, they are mostly embedded
 in viscous micro-structures at the individual level 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "peters_effects_2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, but are still displaced by a common flow at the larger scale, due to turbulenc
e.
 Viscosity decreases diffusivity, which can in turn generate an heterogeneous
 landscape by limiting movements and mixing.
 On the other end of the hydrodynamics spectrum, studies on the fluid mechanics
 of phytoplankton show that a turbulent flow, sometimes associated with
 other phenomena such as motility can encourage the formation of clusters
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "reigada_plankton_2003,durham_turbulence_2013,arrieta_microscale_2015,breier_emergence_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Turbulence also affects phytoplankton organism interactions with their
 environment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "guasto_fluid_2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, by increasing nutrient consumption 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "peters_effects_2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and encounter rates with either potential partners or predators 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kiorboe2018mechanistic"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, therefore affecting organism growths: there can be an effect of the general
 movements of water on the ability of individuals to survive and reproduce,
 whether sexually or asexually (by fission).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This leads us to consider demography in the context of environmental variation
 created by hydrodynamics processes.
 Indeed, including simple processes such as reproduction and death in a
 spatial model can also create a patchy environment: individuals are born
 close to their parents, whereas mortality is a global phenomenon, which
 can lead to clusters of `family' by itself 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "young_reproductive_2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 When hydrodynamics processes are considered, provided that the separation
 between parents and offsprings is not too fast to offset family aggregation,
 i.e.
 if turbulence and/or diffusion are not too high, including individual reproduct
ion encourage a strong spatial structure by itself 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "young_reproductive_2001,bouderbala_3d_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Observed patchiness can therefore be reproduced in models taking into account
 basic mechanisms governing the life of phytoplankton organisms.
 This can have a strong impact if we consider the community level: intraspecific
 clustering itself is important as it increases the likelihood of a particle
 interacting with a conspecific as opposed to an heterospecific.
 Knowing that a high intra-to-interspecific interaction strength is associated
 with coexistence in models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "levine_importance_2009,barabas_self-regulation_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and often observed in the field 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "adler_competition_2018,picoche_strong_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, species-specific clustering might be key to diversity maintenance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, spatial models of individuals at the microscale rarely include
 multiple species 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bouderbala_3d_2018,breier_emergence_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, but it is clear that individual clustering can be enforced at the species
 level, as individuals of the same species share common parameters which
 rule their reaction to their environment.
 For example, experiments often relate a major trait of phytoplankton organisms,
 their size, to the viscosity of their environment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "guadayol_microrheology_2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, reaction to turbulence 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barry_shear-induced_2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, or growth rates 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "edwards_allometric_2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 On a more theoretical point of view, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "barton_impact_2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 have already shown that coexistence between organisms of different sizes
 can be increased by the presence of turbulence.
 While taking diversity of organisms into account is the first step towards
 studying coexistence in spatial models, the lack of studies with multiple
 species can be explained by the computational cost of modeling many individuals
, especially as very large numbers are required for phytoplankton organisms
 which can reach 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{6}$
\end_inset

 individuals per liter, for many species.
 Numerical costs could be partially offset by favoring mathematical analyses
 of spatial models, which can predict spatial distributions in many scenarii.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mathematical analyses of spatial models can quantify the degree of clustering
 in the environment by measuring correlations between positions of pairs
 (or more) of particles 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "illian2008statistical"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A model of individuals randomly reproducing and moving in space, which
 is the type we have focused on here, is also called a spatial point process,
 for which a master equation can often be derived 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "dieckmann_relaxation_2000,birch_master_2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to describe the behaviour of the particles through time.
 The moment measures, which can be seen as the extension of moments of random
 variables, can also be used to compute the expected characteristics of
 the spatial distribution of individuals 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "plank_spatial_2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, the moments of a process are mainly mathematical quantities which
 then need to be related to ecological processes (see, e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "bolker_spatial_1999"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, in which possible spatial strategies for population survival are identified),
 an endeavour often lacking in phytoplankton spatial models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, we present the Brownian Bug Model (BBM), a 3D, individual-based model
 including turbulence and diffusion, as well as births and deaths, based
 on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "young_reproductive_2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, with parameter values adapted to the physical properties of the environment
 and the organisms we study.
 We differentiate between organisms of different sizes and simulate multiple
 species within a single community.
 We are able to provide both numerical simulations and analytical formula
 to quantify the degree of intra- and interspecific clustering of organisms,
 which enables us to characterize the composition of their vicinity for
 different distances from a particle, and use this information to make informed
 guess about mechanisms supporting diversity within different communities
 of phytoplankton.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Material and methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Brownian bug model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Brownian Bug Model (BBM) describes the dynamics of particles going through
 demographic processes in a turbulent and viscous environment, in continuous
 space and time.
 It has been developed in its 2-dimension, monospecific version in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "young_reproductive_2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which we now extend to 3 dimensions and to 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 species having specific demographic and hydrodynamic properties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this model, we consider several populations of particles, each individual
 being characterized by its species 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and its position 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}^{T}=(x\,y\,z)$
\end_inset

.
 The population dynamics are modeled by a linear birth-death process with
 birth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and death rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 Each particle independently follows a Brownian motion with diffusivity
 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, and is advected by a common stochastic flow modeling the turbulence with
 stretching parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, meaning that the separation 
\begin_inset Formula $s(t)$
\end_inset

 between two points previously on top of each other follows 
\begin_inset Formula $s(t)\varpropto e^{3\gamma t}$
\end_inset

.
 We focus here on ecologically relevant quantities which can be extracted
 from this model, both analytically and numerically.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
