\begin_layout Subsection*
Characterization of the spatial distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be the observation window we are working on (here, the cube).
 The state of the system at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 can be described as a collection of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 populations, where the population of species 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is made of 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{i}$
\end_inset

 particles randomly distributed in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, with positions 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}_{i}=[\boldsymbol{x}_{1,i},\boldsymbol{x}_{2,i},...\boldsymbol{x}_{k_{i},i}]$
\end_inset

.
 It is a realization of the spatial point process deriving from a stochastic,
 spatialized individual-based model such as the Brownian Bug Model.
 One of the most common methods to describe a spatial point process is through
 its moments, that can be theoretically derived and allow us to check our
 simulations.
 Here, we also present the dominance index, on which we focus later on for
 its ecological relevance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Moments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first moment is the intensity of the process, or concentration of particles
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}(t)=\frac{N_{i}(W)}{V(W)}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{i}(W)$
\end_inset

 is the number of particles of species 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in the cube and 
\begin_inset Formula $V(W)=L^{3}$
\end_inset

 is the volume of the cube; it does not give any information regarding the
 spatial distribution, and possibly spatial correlation between particles.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second moment, hereafter referred to as the pair correlation function
 
\begin_inset Formula $g(r,t)$
\end_inset

, or pcf, can be thought of as the mean number of points at distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 of a particle.
 If we define 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{j}(t)$
\end_inset

 the concentrations of species 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 respectively, and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{ij}(r,t)$
\end_inset

 the probability of finding a particle of species 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in the sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $dV_{1}$
\end_inset

 and a particle of species 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in the sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $dV_{2}$
\end_inset

 where the centers of 
\begin_inset Formula $dV_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
